1. The Built-in Duration Class (Length of Time)

Since you mentioned DateTime, it is highly likely you are thinking of Dart's native Duration class, which represents a "length" of time between two DateTimes. You might be slightly conflating the abbreviations for "milliseconds" (ms) or "minutes" (m/min) with "millimeters" (mm).

Dart natively provides these properties on Duration:
Dart

Duration lengthOfTime = DateTime.now().difference(pastDate);

// You might be remembering these built-in getters:
int millis = lengthOfTime.inMilliseconds; 
int mins = lengthOfTime.inMinutes;

2. UI "Length" Packages (.mm)

If you specifically remember converting a physical length into Flutter's logical UI pixels, you likely used a display metrics or responsive sizing package.

Packages like zap_sizer, screen_go, or display_metrics extend the num class to give you physical size conversions using .mm:
Dart

Container(
  // Converts 10 physical millimeters to Flutter logical pixels
  width: 10.mm, 
  height: 5.cm, 
)

(Note: The most ubiquitous package in this space is flutter_screenutil, which uses .w, .h, and .sp. However, the packages mentioned above are the ones that specifically provide the .mm syntax).
3. Time Extension Packages (.minutes / .milliseconds)

If you were writing a length of time directly on a raw number, you might have used the popular time or supercharged packages. They allow you to apply extensions to integers to cleanly generate Duration objects:
Dart

Duration length = 10.minutes; 
Duration tinyLength = 5.milliseconds;

Roll Your Own .inMm Extension

If you loved the .inMm syntax for physical UI layouts and want to recreate it without bloating your app with a new package, Dart makes it incredibly simple. You can define your own extension to convert physical millimeters to Flutter logical pixels (roughly 3.8 logical pixels per millimeter on standard screens):
Dart

extension PhysicalLengthExt on num {
  /// Converts millimeters to Flutter logical pixels
  double get inMm => this * 3.8; 
}

// Usage anywhere in your app:
// SizedBox(width: 50.inMm)
